paragraphs.text: %md. <center> ![ML Logo](http://spark-mooc.github.io/web-assets/images/CS190.1x_Banner_300.png) </center># Linear Regression LabThis lab covers a common supervised learning pipeline, using a subset of the [Million Song Dataset](http://labrosa.ee.columbia.edu/millionsong/) from the [UCI Machine Learning Repository](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/YearPredictionMSD). Our goal is to train a linear regression model to predict the release year of a song given a set of audio features. A linear regression looks as follows:. <center>![Linear Regression](http://scikit-learn.org/stable/_images/sphx_glr_plot_ols_001.png) </center>The ML proces for linear regression is similar to the proces of the decision tree we saw in the class lab. ## This Lab will cover:* Part 0: Load modules* Part 1: Read and check the initial dataset* Intermezzo: Nice visualization with SQL* Part 2: Prepare data structure* Part 3: Split data* Part 4: Create a linear regresson model* Part 5: Make predictions and evaluate the linear regression model

Linear Regression Lab

This lab covers a common supervised learning pipeline, using a subset of the Million Song Dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. Our goal is to train a linear regression model to predict the release year of a song given a set of audio features. A linear regression looks as follows:
.

The ML proces for linear regression is similar to the proces of the decision tree we saw in the class lab.

This Lab will cover:

  • Part 0: Load modules
  • Part 1: Read and check the initial dataset
  • Intermezzo: Nice visualization with SQL
  • Part 2: Prepare data structure
  • Part 3: Split data
  • Part 4: Create a linear regresson model
  • Part 5: Make predictions and evaluate the linear regression model

## Part 2: Prepare data structure

Like a Spark ML Decision Tree, a Spark ML Linear Regression requires two input columns an **labelCol** and **featuresCol**. In this specific case, the labelColl is the "_c0" column.
Next to that, there are multiple columns containing independent variables (_c1, ..., _c12). These variables need to be combined into a featureCol that contains a vector (=list). In this Part, two things are done:

> Note that here the _c0 column is already float, so no need to fit a `StringIndexer()`
